<section xmlns="http://xml.house.gov/schemas/uslm/1.0" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="-uslm-lc:I80" id="idf6925554-2930-11f1-96a8-b9bd2a0a99b5" identifier="/us/usc/t46/s11507"><num value="11507">§ 11507.</num><heading> Surrender of offending officers</heading><content>
<p style="-uslm-lc:I11" class="indent0">When an officer of a vessel of the United States (except the master) has violated <ref href="/us/usc/t18/s2191">section 2191 of title 18</ref>, and the master has actual knowledge of the offense or if complaint is made within 3 days after reaching port, the master shall surrender the offending officer to the proper authorities. If the master fails to use diligence to comply with this section and the offender escapes, the owner, the master, and the vessel are liable for damages to the individual unlawfully punished.</p>
</content><sourceCredit id="idf6925555-2930-11f1-96a8-b9bd2a0a99b5">(<ref href="/us/pl/98/89">Pub. L. 98–89</ref>, <date date="1983-08-26">Aug. 26, 1983</date>, <ref href="/us/stat/97/584">97 Stat. 584</ref>.)</sourceCredit>
